-------BINARY TREE------

Each node has at most 2 children (left and right)
Structure is simple and easy to implement
Not always balanced (can become skewed)
Used in expression trees, BST, traversals
Mostly used in main memory (RAM)

---------B-TREE-------

Each node can have multiple children (more than 2)
Always balanced (all leaves at same level)
Structure is complex compared to binary tree
Used in databases and file systems
Optimized for disk storage and fast searching

--------DIFFERENCES-----

Binary Tree → Max 2 children, simple
B-Tree → Many children, balanced, used in databases
